      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Pride of Long Island</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Nassau County (NY) Exec Thomas S Gulotta letter scores those Suffolk County elements that gloat at Nassau's woes (Sept 26 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''As Nassau Sinks, Suffolk Gloats'' (news article, Sept. 26):</p>
        <p>Most issues confronting the residents of Long Island transcend geographic boundaries. That said, Nassau County's strengths should not be overlooked.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''As Nassau Sinks, Suffolk Gloats'' (news article, Sept. 26):</p>
        <p>Most issues confronting the residents of Long Island transcend geographic boundaries. That said, Nassau County's strengths should not be overlooked.</p>
        <p>Nassau's general county property tax has been cut or frozen for eight out of nine years. We have one of the lowest unemployment rates in the state, and our crime rate, our lowest in 28 years, is lower than Suffolk's. Our residential property values are higher than Suffolk's, and our commercial vacancy rates are the lowest in years.</p>
        <p>When Suffolk municipalities faced bankruptcy as the result of Suffolk's overassessment of the Shoreham facility, Nassau didn't gloat; we voluntarily took part in a settlement to ensure Suffolk's fiscal stability. I would not take part in bashing Suffolk then, but neither will I tolerate it from others for Nassau.</p>
        <p>THOMAS S. GULOTTA  Nassau County Executive  Mineola, N.Y., Sept. 28, 2000</p>
      </block>
